Multidisciplinary research aimed at addressing and modifying the excessive cancer incidence and/or mortality rates, the lower cancer survival rates, or the inadequate cancer prevention and control services for special populations.  The term "special populations" refers to those population segments that may experience, or are known to experience, high cancer rates and/or are underserved in terms of cancer prevention and control programs.  Special populations include Alaskan natives, American Indians, Hispanics, Asian- Americans, Blacks, blue-collar groups, the elderly, lower-income groups, native Hawaiians, and American Samoans. (DEA-CAACT)

value.value: Goal: we now have very focused targets against which to direct prevention and therapy efforts. The Molecular Targets Initiative will seek to discover and develop novel prevention, therapeutic, diagnostic, and imaging agents based on our understanding of these targets.  (NCI Web)

A semisynthetic derivative of the nucleoside-like antineoplastic antibiotic spicamycin, originally isolated from the bacterium Streptomyces alanosinicus.
